## Ergonomic Workstation Improvement

Poor workstation setup is one of the most common sources of musculoskeletal strain — and one of the easiest to correct. The images below show the same workstation before and after a targeted ergonomic assessment.

Drag the slider to reveal the changes, or use the arrow keys if you prefer keyboard navigation.

### Before assessment
as: comparison
style: slider

/assets/workstation-before.jpg
alt: Workstation before assessment — monitor below eye level, keyboard on desk surface with no wrist support, chair seat too low causing upward reach, cables scattered across the floor

### After assessment

/assets/workstation-after.jpg
alt: Workstation after assessment — monitor raised to eye level on an adjustable arm, keyboard tray at elbow height with a padded wrist rest, chair adjusted so feet rest flat, cables routed and secured

--

### What changed

The assessment addressed four risk factors in a single adjustment session:

| Risk factor | Before | After |
| Monitor height | Below eye level, causing neck flexion | Raised to neutral — top of screen at eye level |
| Keyboard position | On desk surface, shoulders elevated | Keyboard tray at elbow height, shoulders relaxed |
| Seat height | Too low, arms reaching upward | Adjusted so feet flat, thighs parallel to floor |
| Cable management | Loose cables across floor (trip hazard) | Routed and secured with cable clips |

> Ergonomic improvements do not require expensive equipment. Adjusting what is already at the workstation resolves most issues.
as: note
color: success
style: outline

